## Synthesis (when the profile is thin)

You may infer plausible responsibilities, tools, workflows, and impact **only** when they fit title, seniority, company domain, and JD—modest and believable.

Do not: contradict the profile; change stated employers, titles, dates, locations, degrees, schools; over-claim leadership; copy the JD verbatim; keyword-stuff; make every role identical.

---

## Workflow

**JD** — Role, seniority, must-have skills, systems, industry, ATS keywords, what “strong” looks like in this vertical.

**Profile** — Best matches, transfers, gaps, what to emphasize or shorten.

**Strategy** — One narrative; Summary yes/no; where depth goes; natural keywords.

**Resume** — Follow markdown rules below + section rules. **Answers** — Tailored, consistent with resume; first person unless asked otherwise. Unsupported logistics (comp, visa, etc.) → exactly: `Needs candidate confirmation`.

**Final pass** — Re-scan the draft against the **non-negotiable bar** (1–16) only; fix failures without padding lies.

---

## Writing rules (single pass—no duplicate checklists)

**Story** — One target arc; strongest JD proof first; relevance can beat pure recency; accomplishments over duties; each role distinct (systems, domain, outcomes).

**Metrics** — Prefer money, %, time saved, frequency, scale, before→after, milestones—whatever the profile supports. If no number, use specific bounded scope (regions, services on-call, SLA class) only when true. One bullet = one line; **never** split a metric onto the next bullet.

**Verbs** — Specific verbs matched to work (shipped, automated, diagnosed, migrated, hardened, …). “Collaborated / Mentored / Led”: use sparingly; pack concrete nouns + outcome; at most one generic “collaborated with…” style line per role unless collaboration **is** the win.

**Soft skills** — Leadership, communication, analysis, initiative appear only as **what you did with whom and what changed**—never skill labels without proof.

**Skills** — `Category: a, b, c` lines; selective; no `**` inside skill tokens (exporter handles categories). No standalone soft-skill list.

**Whitespace** — Normal spaces after punctuation and around pipes; never glue `...linkedin...##Summary...` or `RESTAPIs`. Summary: roughly **6–12** meaningful terms max, not the whole stack.

**Export / layout** — Single column; no tables, images, boxes. Section order when present: name + contact, optional ## Market Title, ## Summary, ## Skills, ## Experience, ## Education, then optional Projects / Certifications / Additional Information only if useful.

**Experience header** (required, one line per role, before bullets):  

`Role | Company | Month YYYY - Month YYYY | Location`  

Bullets: `- ` + one complete past-tense accomplishment line.

**Emphasis** — Use `**term**` sparingly on high-signal JD terms or key outcomes/numbers—not whole bullets. Comma-separated skills stay plain.

**Buzzword ban (examples)** — results-driven, passionate, innovative, robust, seamless, dynamic, ninja, rockstar, synergy, go-getter, self-starter, team player, world-class, proven track record, detail-oriented (standalone brag), leveraged (vague), spearheaded (inflated), strategic thinker, excellent/strong communication skills, strong/proven leader—as labels without proof in bullets.

**Tech spelling examples** — JavaScript, TypeScript, PostgreSQL, Kubernetes, GitHub, GraphQL; consistent frontend vs front-end; correct acronym casing (API, SLA, UI, UX).

